00:05:06.680 --> 00:05:10.360
[Amit Varma]: So let me kind of start off by asking you this.

00:05:10.360 --> 00:05:16.480
[Amit Varma]: I'd done an episode on foreign policy in general, a few weeks ago with your colleague Nitin

00:05:16.480 --> 00:05:17.600
[Amit Varma]: Pai.

00:05:17.600 --> 00:05:22.120
[Amit Varma]: And Nitin pointed out the various different schools of foreign policy.

00:05:22.120 --> 00:05:26.440
[Amit Varma]: And about China, what he said in particular was that the impression I got from that episode

00:05:26.440 --> 00:05:31.880
[Amit Varma]: was that China has sort of had a very insular foreign policy where it doesn't look outward,

00:05:31.880 --> 00:05:37.960
[Amit Varma]: it's kind of happy with what it is and just defending its borders and so on and so forth.

00:05:37.960 --> 00:05:39.600
[Amit Varma]: What has, is that correct?

00:05:39.600 --> 00:05:44.600
[Amit Varma]: What has been the historical outlook of China towards the rest of the world?

00:05:44.600 --> 00:05:47.760
[Guest]: And is that changing?

00:05:47.760 --> 00:05:48.760
[Guest]: That's a good question.

00:05:48.760 --> 00:05:52.280
[Guest]: I mean, I wouldn't characterize China's foreign policy outlook as insular.

00:05:52.280 --> 00:05:54.360
[Guest]: I wouldn't do so at any point of time.

00:05:54.360 --> 00:06:00.280
[Guest]: I mean, when you talk about China, what you really need to think of is that this is a

00:06:00.280 --> 00:06:07.240
[Guest]: political entity which has been there for at least 2000 plus 2500 years.

00:06:07.240 --> 00:06:12.440
[Guest]: And that's how the Chinese also view themselves as a civilization, obviously much older, 5000

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:18.240
[Guest]: odd years, but as a political unified entity from about 2000 years onwards.

00:06:18.240 --> 00:06:22.480
[Guest]: And throughout that period, there have been periods of expansion, there have been periods

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:25.240
[Guest]: of being insular.

00:06:25.240 --> 00:06:32.960
[Guest]: But the idea that China remains a serious actor internationally has been a core idea

00:06:32.960 --> 00:06:37.600
[Guest]: within the political system, whether it was during the dynasties, or whether it is during

00:06:37.600 --> 00:06:40.240
[Guest]: the People's Republic era.

00:06:40.240 --> 00:06:44.840
[Guest]: So just a quick sense, I think, I presume one of the concepts that Nitin must have spoken

00:06:44.840 --> 00:06:52.560
[Guest]: about was this concept of Tianxia, which is a Chinese term referring to a broader concept

00:06:52.560 --> 00:06:54.840
[Guest]: of all under the heaven.

00:06:54.840 --> 00:06:59.480
[Guest]: This is the fundamental concept which places, from which we derive the idea of the Middle

00:06:59.480 --> 00:07:00.480
[Guest]: Kingdom.

00:07:00.480 --> 00:07:04.960
[Guest]: So when you see a kingdom or a polity talking about itself as the center of the world as

00:07:04.960 --> 00:07:10.160
[Guest]: the Middle Kingdom, you can't really see it as insular in that sense.

00:07:10.160 --> 00:07:12.120
[Amit Varma]: That's where I derived that logic from.

00:07:12.120 --> 00:07:16.920
[Amit Varma]: And what's traditionally been China's approach towards the world, like one of the things

00:07:16.920 --> 00:07:22.040
[Amit Varma]: that you know, Nitin did speak about is how international relations really evolved during

00:07:22.040 --> 00:07:26.800
[Amit Varma]: the 20th century with different nation states looking outwards and trying to establish a

00:07:26.800 --> 00:07:30.520
[Amit Varma]: particular place for themselves in the world.

00:07:30.520 --> 00:07:35.640
[Amit Varma]: How has that evolved from China, the way China sees itself vis-a-vis the rest of the world?

00:07:35.640 --> 00:07:38.800
[Amit Varma]: And has ideology had an impact on that?

00:07:38.800 --> 00:07:41.320
[Guest]: Okay, so I think this is great.

00:07:41.320 --> 00:07:43.240
[Guest]: So this picks up on the point of the Middle Kingdom.

00:07:43.240 --> 00:07:45.680
[Guest]: And then that's where I'll build further from.

00:07:45.680 --> 00:07:52.360
[Guest]: So the idea of the Middle Kingdom is this central body through which everything emanates,

00:07:52.360 --> 00:07:56.600
[Guest]: and civilization and culture emanates from it, commerce and trade emanates from it.

00:07:56.600 --> 00:07:58.000
[Guest]: And it's the center of the world.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:03.680
[Guest]: So in that sense, it sees itself or it saw itself as the center of the world, as a exceptional

00:08:03.680 --> 00:08:07.360
[Guest]: state in this larger international space.

00:08:07.360 --> 00:08:14.720
[Guest]: Now, if I was to fast forward that, to say 1949, from the fall of the Qing dynasty in

00:08:14.720 --> 00:08:22.680
[Guest]: 1911, 1912 to 1949, that chaotic period in China, where you have colonization, you have

00:08:22.680 --> 00:08:27.640
[Guest]: a civil war between nationalists and the communists, and you have the World War invasions by the

00:08:27.640 --> 00:08:29.280
[Guest]: Japanese.

00:08:29.280 --> 00:08:32.680
[Guest]: And China goes through this entire period of turmoil, where it's questioning its place

00:08:32.680 --> 00:08:33.800
[Guest]: in the world.

00:08:33.800 --> 00:08:38.280
[Guest]: And it's wondering where the idea of this Middle Kingdom has gone, where the glory of

00:08:38.280 --> 00:08:39.900
[Guest]: the Middle Kingdom has gone.

00:08:39.900 --> 00:08:43.880
[Guest]: And then in 1949, we have the People's Republic, which emerges.

00:08:43.880 --> 00:08:49.840
[Guest]: And the People's Republic under Mao Zedong has an idea of itself as a revolutionary force.

00:08:49.840 --> 00:08:56.600
[Guest]: So it sees its role in the international arena as a political entity that must promote revolution.

00:08:56.600 --> 00:08:59.880
[Guest]: So this is obviously with the Soviet Union.

00:08:59.880 --> 00:09:01.000
[Guest]: So China goes through that.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:04.760
[Guest]: That's your first modern China, the People's Republic phase, where you establish the idea

00:09:04.760 --> 00:09:07.080
[Guest]: that you want to be a revolutionary force.

00:09:07.080 --> 00:09:13.040
[Guest]: And then by the late 1970s, after Mao Zedong's death and the arrival of Deng Xiaoping in

00:09:13.040 --> 00:09:18.160
[Guest]: charge of China's affairs, you have a new architecture of foreign policy, which comes

00:09:18.160 --> 00:09:22.480
[Guest]: out, which is not personality driven by Mao, which is not looking at revolution, which

00:09:22.480 --> 00:09:28.280
[Guest]: is looking at China as a state within the community of states, and which is looking

00:09:28.280 --> 00:09:31.600
[Guest]: at China as an actor in that arena.

00:09:31.600 --> 00:09:38.160
[Guest]: And Deng Xiaoping goes on to develop this concept of Tao Guang Yang Hui, which essentially

00:09:38.160 --> 00:09:43.360
[Guest]: roughly translates into hide your strength and bide your time, although the actual translation

00:09:43.360 --> 00:09:47.220
[Guest]: is not that, but that's broadly what it's accepted to imply.

00:09:47.220 --> 00:09:51.040
[Guest]: And what happens with that is that it's China now focusing on its own domestic growth, on

00:09:51.040 --> 00:09:55.760
[Guest]: its economy, on its immediate interests, as opposed to this idea of a revolution, of a

00:09:55.760 --> 00:09:57.960
[Guest]: global revolution.

00:09:57.960 --> 00:10:02.280
[Guest]: And from that era, we come to today, which is a new era under Xi Jinping.

00:10:02.280 --> 00:10:03.840
[Guest]: He defines it as a new era.

00:10:03.840 --> 00:10:05.800
[Guest]: That's the phrase that he uses.

00:10:05.800 --> 00:10:11.200
[Guest]: And the idea now is that China has come to a point where it can express itself internationally.

00:10:11.200 --> 00:10:16.400
[Guest]: It can pursue broader interests, and it no longer needs to necessarily hide its strength

00:10:16.400 --> 00:10:17.660
[Guest]: and bide its time.

00:10:17.660 --> 00:10:21.720
[Amit Varma]: It actually needs to express itself more on the international stage.

00:10:21.720 --> 00:10:26.920
[Amit Varma]: And what are these broader interests that under Xi Jinping, under this new era that

00:10:26.920 --> 00:10:30.680
[Guest]: China is now exploring?

00:10:30.680 --> 00:10:36.480
[Guest]: So I think these broader interests are that they build on the interests that have been

00:10:36.480 --> 00:10:38.920
[Guest]: defined over the decades.

00:10:38.920 --> 00:10:43.920
[Guest]: So one of the concepts that is very prevalent in Chinese foreign policy is the idea of core

00:10:43.920 --> 00:10:45.720
[Guest]: interests.

00:10:45.720 --> 00:10:48.960
[Guest]: As the name suggests, core interests, these are fundamental.

00:10:48.960 --> 00:10:55.080
[Guest]: So these are the need to sustain development, economic development, the need to ensure territorial

00:10:55.080 --> 00:10:56.640
[Guest]: integrity.

00:10:56.640 --> 00:11:02.240
[Guest]: One must remember that China has territorial disputes in the east and the west, and even

00:11:02.240 --> 00:11:04.200
[Guest]: somewhere in the north.

00:11:04.200 --> 00:11:08.040
[Guest]: So it's important for the Chinese, therefore, to ensure the integrity of their nation.

00:11:08.040 --> 00:11:09.280
[Guest]: That's how they see it as.

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:15.920
[Guest]: So the stability in Tibet, stability in Xinjiang, the border dispute with India, maritime disputes

00:11:15.920 --> 00:11:21.520
[Guest]: in the South China Sea, the Senkakus and Diaoyu dispute in the East China Sea.

00:11:21.520 --> 00:11:26.280
[Guest]: These are all factors that have built over a period of time as core interests.

00:11:26.280 --> 00:11:32.920
[Guest]: So development, territorial integrity, broader economic security in which you're expanding

00:11:32.920 --> 00:11:33.920
[Guest]: your enterprises.

00:11:33.920 --> 00:11:40.080
[Guest]: They are going global and they are capturing market share, revenues, resources internationally

00:11:40.080 --> 00:11:42.160
[Guest]: to ensure domestic development.

00:11:42.160 --> 00:11:46.920
[Guest]: All of these are core interests which lead to a more fundamental core interest, if you

00:11:46.920 --> 00:11:53.640
[Guest]: may, and that is the stability and the continuation of the rule of the Communist Party of China.

00:11:53.640 --> 00:11:58.800
[Guest]: That is a predominant interest of the party, is for the system to survive.

00:11:58.800 --> 00:12:01.480
[Guest]: So under Xi Jinping, he's built on that.

00:12:01.480 --> 00:12:04.900
[Guest]: And you would see the idea of the Belt and Road.

00:12:04.900 --> 00:12:08.200
[Guest]: You would see the idea of global governance reforms.

00:12:08.200 --> 00:12:14.120
[Guest]: All of these being part of China's core interests, sort of accumulating within China's core interests,

00:12:14.120 --> 00:12:18.360
[Guest]: because it's through these that China becomes a bigger actor internationally, and it also

00:12:18.360 --> 00:12:20.040
[Guest]: secures itself.

00:12:20.040 --> 00:12:24.200
[Guest]: So that's where I would define the broad set of interests that the Chinese have.

00:12:24.200 --> 00:12:29.040
[Amit Varma]: So you sort of spoke about the focus then being on these three areas, that is, China

00:12:29.040 --> 00:12:34.680
[Amit Varma]: continues developing, China looks after its territorial interests, whether it's in Tibet

00:12:34.680 --> 00:12:41.320
[Amit Varma]: or the South China Sea or wherever, and also the third one being broader economic security.

00:12:41.320 --> 00:12:45.920
[Amit Varma]: But one interesting thing you said, which sort of intrigued me is that, and I hope I

00:12:45.920 --> 00:12:51.640
[Amit Varma]: understood it correctly, is that the reason for this is because Xi Jinping feels that

00:12:51.640 --> 00:12:57.680
[Amit Varma]: the party has to continue structurally being the entity in charge in China.

00:12:57.680 --> 00:13:03.080
[Amit Varma]: And the one thing that ensures that is if China itself is secure and stable within the

00:13:03.080 --> 00:13:04.080
[Amit Varma]: world.

00:13:04.080 --> 00:13:08.540
[Amit Varma]: So in that sense, all of these are a means to the end with the end being the continuation

00:13:08.540 --> 00:13:10.240
[Amit Varma]: of the party in power.

00:13:10.240 --> 00:13:11.880
[Amit Varma]: Did I understand it correctly?

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:13.560
[Guest]: Yeah, absolutely.

00:13:13.560 --> 00:13:19.760
[Guest]: So if you read through Xi Jinping's speeches and government documents, what you will find

00:13:19.760 --> 00:13:24.920
[Guest]: is that, and this was specifically noted by Xi in the 19th Party Congress, which is this

00:13:24.920 --> 00:13:28.320
[Guest]: meeting that happens once every five years.

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:32.960
[Guest]: It elects a new Politburo, a new Politburo Standing Committee, which are your central

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:37.640
[Guest]: bodies that run the party, and also elects a new General Secretary every 10 years.

00:13:37.640 --> 00:13:41.280
[Guest]: So Xi Jinping this year started his second term as the General Secretary of the Communist

00:13:41.280 --> 00:13:42.280
[Guest]: Party.

00:13:42.280 --> 00:13:47.360
[Guest]: So at this important meeting, which happened in October last year, Xi Jinping delivered

00:13:47.360 --> 00:13:48.720
[Guest]: a very long speech.

00:13:48.720 --> 00:13:51.920
[Guest]: It was, I think, about three and a half hours long.

00:13:51.920 --> 00:13:57.080
[Guest]: And one of the central ideas of the speech was the concept that the party has to have

00:13:57.080 --> 00:14:01.440
[Guest]: a say in every sphere of society in life.

00:14:01.440 --> 00:14:04.260
[Guest]: The party must penetrate everything.

00:14:04.260 --> 00:14:09.520
[Guest]: From there, Xi Jinping went on in March, where he became the president for the second time.

00:14:09.520 --> 00:14:14.120
[Guest]: And again, at that meeting, he delivered a speech, which was mercifully just 30 odd minutes

00:14:14.120 --> 00:14:15.360
[Guest]: long.

00:14:15.360 --> 00:14:19.200
[Guest]: And in that speech, he reiterates these points.

00:14:19.200 --> 00:14:24.600
[Guest]: And thereafter, there is a reorganization of government, where the party is further

00:14:24.600 --> 00:14:26.840
[Guest]: merged with the government.

00:14:26.840 --> 00:14:32.840
[Guest]: So this ensures that the party survives, the party begins to further cannibalize government

00:14:32.840 --> 00:14:34.960
[Guest]: and state institutions.

00:14:34.960 --> 00:14:39.640
[Guest]: And that's one of those fundamental goals, whether it's domestically or internationally,

00:14:39.640 --> 00:14:43.520
[Guest]: the survival of the party is a precondition for anything else to happen.

00:14:43.520 --> 00:14:48.120
[Amit Varma]: And this reminds me of the old slogan we had in India back in the good old days, I say

00:14:48.120 --> 00:14:49.120
[Amit Varma]: ironically.

00:14:49.120 --> 00:14:50.840
[Amit Varma]: India is Indira, Indira is India.

00:14:50.840 --> 00:14:56.520
[Amit Varma]: And here it would seem there are sort of two relevant slogans, one, of course, being that

00:14:56.520 --> 00:14:58.920
[Amit Varma]: China is the party, the party is China.

00:14:58.920 --> 00:15:03.320
[Amit Varma]: And the other could even be that Xi is a party, the party is Xi, because in a sense, what

00:15:03.320 --> 00:15:08.200
[Amit Varma]: Xi has also been trying to do, and again, correct me if I've misunderstood it, is consolidate

00:15:08.200 --> 00:15:16.000
[Amit Varma]: his own hold of the party, even as the party consolidates its dominance over Chinese institutions.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:17.000
[Amit Varma]: Is that correct?

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.120
[Guest]: No, that's absolutely correct.

00:15:19.120 --> 00:15:24.280
[Guest]: And so much of Xi Jinping's first five years in power, I mean, he came into power in late

00:15:24.280 --> 00:15:29.000
[Guest]: 2012, became the president in March 2013.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:35.400
[Guest]: And what he's done is that he's structurally broken down networks of patronage in the name

00:15:35.400 --> 00:15:37.480
[Guest]: of fighting corruption.

00:15:37.480 --> 00:15:45.240
[Guest]: And he's also used that anti-corruption campaign to eliminate rivals, target rival factions,

00:15:45.240 --> 00:15:52.560
[Guest]: streamline government processes, place confidence in key positions, and centralise the entire

00:15:52.560 --> 00:15:54.920
[Guest]: decision making apparatus further.

00:15:54.920 --> 00:16:00.280
[Guest]: Now, this might sound quite odd to a lot of people who generally look at China from the

00:16:00.280 --> 00:16:05.280
[Guest]: news and view the Communist Party as this one uniform actor.

00:16:05.280 --> 00:16:08.360
[Guest]: It's quite a divided actor in some ways.

00:16:08.360 --> 00:16:12.640
[Guest]: And decision making can get paralysed at multiple levels.

00:16:12.640 --> 00:16:17.480
[Guest]: And that's evident from the fact that Xi's had to look to centralise so much authority

00:16:17.480 --> 00:16:21.600
[Guest]: in order to ensure that decisions are taken and executed.

00:16:21.600 --> 00:16:22.600
[Guest]: So he's done that.

00:16:22.600 --> 00:16:23.600
[Guest]: And that's resulted in this.

00:16:23.600 --> 00:16:28.740
[Guest]: I mean, the culmination of all of this was the removal of presidential term limits in

00:16:28.740 --> 00:16:34.040
[Guest]: March this year, where now Xi Jinping effectively can remain president for life if he wants

00:16:34.040 --> 00:16:35.120
[Guest]: to.

00:16:35.120 --> 00:16:40.960
[Guest]: So he has, yes, centralised the party, he's renamed, he's got his name entered in the

00:16:40.960 --> 00:16:48.080
[Guest]: constitution of the country with his banner idea, which is Xi Jinping thought.

00:16:48.080 --> 00:16:54.800
[Guest]: So that's now a part of the Communist Party and the Chinese state's constitution.

00:16:54.800 --> 00:16:57.240
[Guest]: And that's a guiding vision now for the state.

00:16:57.240 --> 00:17:03.240
[Guest]: So he's elevated himself to a position which is only, if not equal to, then probably secondary

00:17:03.240 --> 00:17:06.740
[Guest]: to Mao, because it's very difficult to be equal to Mao.

00:17:06.740 --> 00:17:09.040
[Guest]: But he's gotten himself to a position like that.

00:17:09.040 --> 00:17:14.420
[Guest]: And so yeah, it has become that the party has become Xi Jinping's party.

00:17:14.420 --> 00:17:18.800
[Guest]: The other idea that you spoke about, which was the party being China and China being

00:17:18.800 --> 00:17:23.980
[Guest]: the party, I think the Communist Party would like for people to think that way.

00:17:23.980 --> 00:17:29.280
[Guest]: But we must remember that the Communist Party of China has about 90 million members at the

00:17:29.280 --> 00:17:30.960
[Guest]: max.

00:17:30.960 --> 00:17:36.680
[Guest]: And China is a far more diverse, far more vibrant country in that sense.

00:17:36.680 --> 00:17:43.600
[Guest]: There is a lot of different views and opinions that are expressed, and the party remains

00:17:43.600 --> 00:17:48.680
[Guest]: this firm actor, which would like the image internationally to be that China is the party

00:17:48.680 --> 00:17:50.180
[Guest]: and the party is China.

00:17:50.180 --> 00:17:52.680
[Guest]: But China is far more diverse than that.

00:17:52.680 --> 00:17:56.320
[Amit Varma]: But I mean, are there other actors on the political stage, for example, apart from the

00:17:56.320 --> 00:17:57.320
[Amit Varma]: party?

00:17:57.320 --> 00:18:00.680
[Amit Varma]: I mean, China's not a democracy, the party basically rules it, right?

00:18:00.680 --> 00:18:02.040
[Guest]: Yes, it does.

00:18:02.040 --> 00:18:03.040
[Guest]: It does rule it.

00:18:03.040 --> 00:18:08.880
[Guest]: But when I say that China is very diverse, it's not necessarily in the context of formal

00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:10.240
[Guest]: political activity.

00:18:10.240 --> 00:18:15.040
[Guest]: Because yes, you have eight other political parties that operate within China.

00:18:15.040 --> 00:18:18.240
[Guest]: They operate under the guiding hand of the Communist Party of China.

00:18:18.240 --> 00:18:21.040
[Guest]: So they don't effectively have any autonomy.

00:18:21.040 --> 00:18:23.120
[Guest]: They don't really contest elections.

00:18:23.120 --> 00:18:27.360
[Guest]: Elections in China occur at certain levels, at the village level.

00:18:27.360 --> 00:18:29.800
[Guest]: Those are experiments that are being conducted.

00:18:29.800 --> 00:18:33.680
[Guest]: But predominantly, the political system is run through the party system.

00:18:33.680 --> 00:18:39.360
[Guest]: So the party has a parallel system from center to provinces and further down to the state

00:18:39.360 --> 00:18:43.000
[Guest]: system of central government, provincial government and further down.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:45.200
[Guest]: And these two systems intermingle with each other.

00:18:45.200 --> 00:18:50.480
[Guest]: So there isn't any room for other political actors to actually play any meaningful role.

00:18:50.480 --> 00:18:56.160
[Guest]: But when I say that China is far more diverse, it's because not everybody necessarily, or

00:18:56.160 --> 00:19:02.320
[Guest]: at least a large majority, don't necessarily recognize the party as necessarily this guiding

00:19:02.320 --> 00:19:03.320
[Guest]: light, this force.

00:19:03.320 --> 00:19:08.720
[Guest]: They see the party as an important actor, but they also see themselves as distinct from

00:19:08.720 --> 00:19:09.720
[Guest]: the party.

00:19:09.720 --> 00:19:15.360
[Guest]: A lot of people would like freedom of expression, a lot of people would like freedom of association.

00:19:15.360 --> 00:19:18.240
[Guest]: And so therefore, I don't see necessarily this connect.

00:19:18.240 --> 00:19:22.360
[Guest]: A lot of people would have a different perspective from the party in terms of how the politics

00:19:22.360 --> 00:19:23.760
[Guest]: should be run.

00:19:23.760 --> 00:19:26.880
[Guest]: But it's also about where your interest lies.

00:19:26.880 --> 00:19:28.920
[Guest]: Can you actually append the order?

00:19:28.920 --> 00:19:31.880
[Guest]: Does appending the orders serve your interests?

00:19:31.880 --> 00:19:33.560
[Guest]: So there are multiple factors at play.

00:19:33.560 --> 00:19:37.960
[Guest]: But as a society, if you visit China, what you realize is that there are multiple different

00:19:37.960 --> 00:19:39.560
[Guest]: thoughts.

00:19:39.560 --> 00:19:45.640
[Guest]: And the party's single ideological notions don't necessarily run through society.

00:19:45.640 --> 00:19:48.320
[Guest]: It's not a society which has stopped thinking.

00:19:48.320 --> 00:19:49.320
[Guest]: It's not North Korea.

00:19:49.320 --> 00:19:55.520
[Amit Varma]: Right, so my sort of follow up question to that is, you had mentioned Xi's sort of formulation

00:19:55.520 --> 00:20:02.520
[Amit Varma]: of quote unquote, a new era, which is the sort of outward looking foreign policy.

00:20:02.520 --> 00:20:07.600
[Amit Varma]: Now, is that something that has come from Xi himself or was that part of a developing

00:20:07.600 --> 00:20:09.360
[Amit Varma]: consensus within the party?

00:20:09.360 --> 00:20:13.280
[Amit Varma]: And was it at some point inevitable that China would move in this direction?

00:20:13.280 --> 00:20:16.460
[Guest]: Okay, that's a good question.

00:20:16.460 --> 00:20:22.560
[Guest]: So a lot of this talk of the new era, okay, then the nomenclature for the new era comes

00:20:22.560 --> 00:20:25.160
[Guest]: under Xi Jinping.

00:20:25.160 --> 00:20:31.660
[Guest]: But you can see a shift that's happening in Chinese foreign policy from around 2008 onwards.

00:20:31.660 --> 00:20:36.480
[Guest]: And this coincides with this financial crisis around the world, with the West struggling

00:20:36.480 --> 00:20:39.120
[Guest]: with its banking system.

00:20:39.120 --> 00:20:45.920
[Guest]: And you see, the Chinese essentially adopt a far more aggressive or assertive approach

00:20:45.920 --> 00:20:48.080
[Guest]: in their foreign relations.

00:20:48.080 --> 00:20:52.080
[Guest]: This manifests in the South China Sea.

00:20:52.080 --> 00:20:58.040
[Guest]: This manifests in a remarkable conversation between a Chinese delegation and an American

00:20:58.040 --> 00:21:05.320
[Guest]: delegation, where the Chinese delegation essentially tells the American delegation, responding

00:21:05.320 --> 00:21:10.360
[Guest]: to the credit crisis that's developed in 2008, that there was a point where you were our

00:21:10.360 --> 00:21:12.920
[Guest]: masters and you were our teachers.

00:21:12.920 --> 00:21:13.920
[Guest]: I think the word was teachers.

00:21:13.920 --> 00:21:16.800
[Guest]: Yeah, that you were our teachers when it came to the economy.

00:21:16.800 --> 00:21:22.400
[Guest]: But today you failed, and we will have to find our own course, something to that effect.

00:21:22.400 --> 00:21:27.060
[Guest]: So there's a departure that starts to take place from that point of time.

00:21:27.060 --> 00:21:31.880
[Guest]: And that departure is witnessed in this assertion in the South China Sea, with regard to an

00:21:31.880 --> 00:21:37.440
[Guest]: oil rig with Vietnam, with regard to the Scarborough Shoal, in the context of the China-Philippines

00:21:37.440 --> 00:21:39.920
[Guest]: spat in the South China Sea.

00:21:39.920 --> 00:21:45.240
[Guest]: In 2011-2012, we start seeing tensions with Japan in the East China Sea.

00:21:45.240 --> 00:21:49.760
[Guest]: So you start to see this shift happening at that point of time.

00:21:49.760 --> 00:21:57.880
[Guest]: And the perception is that there is an opportunity right now for us to express ourselves, because

00:21:57.880 --> 00:22:00.720
[Guest]: there is serious turmoil around the world.

00:22:00.720 --> 00:22:04.160
[Guest]: And you can see that America is on a decline.

00:22:04.160 --> 00:22:07.280
[Guest]: And this credit crisis is precipitating that decline further.

00:22:07.280 --> 00:22:11.520
[Guest]: So you see that sort of conversation happening within China.

00:22:11.520 --> 00:22:15.320
[Guest]: And in that milieu is when Xi Jinping comes to power.

00:22:15.320 --> 00:22:19.480
[Guest]: And so there are these two philosophical arguments that are happening when Xi Jinping comes to

00:22:19.480 --> 00:22:21.520
[Guest]: power.

00:22:21.520 --> 00:22:23.400
[Guest]: So there are these two philosophical concepts.

00:22:23.400 --> 00:22:28.960
[Guest]: The first is the Deng Xiaoping concept of Tao Kuang Yang Hui, which I spoke about earlier.

00:22:28.960 --> 00:22:34.280
[Guest]: And the second is this more assertive concept called Fen Fai You Wei.

00:22:34.280 --> 00:22:39.640
[Guest]: Fen Fai You Wei essentially translates into striving for achievement.

00:22:39.640 --> 00:22:46.960
[Guest]: That concept essentially implies that you need to actively shape the international or

00:22:46.960 --> 00:22:49.860
[Guest]: the external environment to suit your interests.

00:22:49.860 --> 00:22:55.800
[Guest]: So that implies a certain assertion in your foreign policy, as opposed to trying to keep

00:22:55.800 --> 00:23:01.360
[Guest]: a low profile and taking advantage of scenarios as and when they arrive to serve your interests.

00:23:01.360 --> 00:23:04.280
[Guest]: And so there is this sort of shift that begins to happen.

00:23:04.280 --> 00:23:09.960
[Guest]: Under Xi Jinping, what we see is that we see this get crystallized into a clearer vision.

00:23:09.960 --> 00:23:15.640
[Guest]: The idea of a new era, the idea of Belt and Road and China actively going global.

00:23:15.640 --> 00:23:21.200
[Guest]: The idea that China is going to invite countries over and political parties over to Beijing

00:23:21.200 --> 00:23:26.480
[Guest]: to shape a discourse on human rights, which is something that the West has dominated.

00:23:26.480 --> 00:23:31.800
[Guest]: The idea that China wants to reshape governance norms, whether it's related to artificial

00:23:31.800 --> 00:23:36.240
[Guest]: intelligence, whether it's related to human rights, whether it's related to lending.

00:23:36.240 --> 00:23:39.880
[Guest]: So it's these sorts of things that start to happen.

00:23:39.880 --> 00:23:45.120
[Guest]: So I would trace this sort of shift in foreign policy starting from about 2008 onwards.

00:23:45.120 --> 00:23:50.720
[Guest]: And under Xi Jinping, it gets crystallized further, it becomes far more public, and China

00:23:50.720 --> 00:23:53.200
[Guest]: becomes far more vocal about it.

00:23:53.200 --> 00:23:55.440
[Guest]: So that's how I would categorize it.

00:23:55.440 --> 00:24:00.120
[Amit Varma]: And what you described as this striving for achievement, how does it manifest itself?

00:24:00.120 --> 00:24:03.200
[Amit Varma]: For example, how is Chinese foreign policy today?

00:24:03.200 --> 00:24:09.400
[Amit Varma]: What are the salient ways in which it is different from Chinese foreign policy of say, 1995?

00:24:09.400 --> 00:24:10.400
[Guest]: So okay, how is it different?

00:24:10.400 --> 00:24:14.800
[Guest]: It's different, firstly, in terms of what is the narrative that is being projected.

00:24:14.800 --> 00:24:20.200
[Guest]: So the narrative today that is being projected is one of China as an innovative, leading

00:24:20.200 --> 00:24:25.760
[Guest]: world power, as opposed to the 1990s, and even through the 2000s, where the narrative

00:24:25.760 --> 00:24:31.320
[Guest]: was essentially about China, a developing power, a developing state, which is eyeing

00:24:31.320 --> 00:24:35.240
[Guest]: a peaceful rise or which is eyeing peaceful development.

00:24:35.240 --> 00:24:37.740
[Guest]: So there is a narrative shift that happens.

00:24:37.740 --> 00:24:43.260
[Guest]: If you look at that in the context of how China now looks at providing aid, providing

00:24:43.260 --> 00:24:49.760
[Guest]: investments to countries, as opposed to wanting to be a recipient of aid and investment.

00:24:49.760 --> 00:24:52.040
[Guest]: So those are sort of few tangible ways where this happens.

00:24:52.040 --> 00:24:56.160
[Guest]: It also happens in the context of expanding military to military engagement.

00:24:56.160 --> 00:24:59.700
[Guest]: China wants to sell weapons, it wants to sell its arms, it wants to build up this defense

00:24:59.700 --> 00:25:01.680
[Guest]: industrial base.

00:25:01.680 --> 00:25:06.640
[Guest]: So from projection to actual changes in these financial support to countries, investment,

00:25:06.640 --> 00:25:12.080
[Guest]: arms sales, the essentially the opening up and going abroad and actually projecting the

00:25:12.080 --> 00:25:15.280
[Guest]: power that you now have built up over time.

00:25:15.280 --> 00:25:16.680
[Amit Varma]: That's the change that happens.

