[Unknown]: And with that, let's continue with your show.

00:26:16.040 --> 00:26:17.960
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene and the unseen, Manoj.

00:26:17.960 --> 00:26:18.960
[Amit Varma]: Thank you, Amit.

00:26:18.960 --> 00:26:25.080
[Amit Varma]: So we were sort of talking about this fundamental change that, you know, happened between the

00:26:25.080 --> 00:26:29.120
[Amit Varma]: era of Deng and the era of Xi, the era of Deng basically being hide your strengths and

00:26:29.120 --> 00:26:35.560
[Amit Varma]: bide your time as, as you put it, which China was content to sort of focus on its own internal

00:26:35.560 --> 00:26:39.000
[Amit Varma]: development and not worry so much about the rest of the world.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:43.800
[Amit Varma]: And Xi's formulation, which, as you pointed out, is something that was happening anyway,

00:26:43.800 --> 00:26:48.760
[Amit Varma]: and it's not necessarily dependent on his person, was that of a new era where China

00:26:48.760 --> 00:26:57.360
[Amit Varma]: takes a much more active role in world affairs, where it tries to sort of sustain its development,

00:26:57.360 --> 00:27:05.080
[Amit Varma]: be more aggressive about its territorial integrity, and search for broader economic security,

00:27:05.080 --> 00:27:09.080
[Amit Varma]: and get more involved in the world, whether it's in terms of, you know, investing in other

00:27:09.080 --> 00:27:14.240
[Amit Varma]: countries around the world, including Africa recently, as you wrote about, on Pragati,

00:27:14.240 --> 00:27:15.240
[Amit Varma]: and so on.

00:27:15.240 --> 00:27:20.240
[Amit Varma]: And all this is very interesting, because this is happening at a time where like you

00:27:20.240 --> 00:27:26.000
[Amit Varma]: refer to the financial crisis of 2008, as sort of one of those points where something

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:33.000
[Amit Varma]: began to turn, or maybe when it became visible, where America sort of losing its grip as a

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:35.240
[Amit Varma]: sole superpower of the world.

00:27:35.240 --> 00:27:39.640
[Amit Varma]: And especially now that, you know, Donald Trump has come on the scene, and he's starting

00:27:39.640 --> 00:27:42.360
[Amit Varma]: these trade wars, and so on and so forth.

00:27:42.360 --> 00:27:48.440
[Amit Varma]: So how has the US, like earlier, for example, the US was content to do its thing and the

00:27:48.440 --> 00:27:52.840
[Amit Varma]: China was content to do its thing and sort of build itself while America did what it

00:27:52.840 --> 00:27:54.400
[Amit Varma]: did and rule the world.

00:27:54.400 --> 00:27:58.960
[Amit Varma]: And now it's almost like, would it be fair to say, number one, that it's bipolar and

00:27:58.960 --> 00:28:05.960
[Amit Varma]: number two, that China is actively trying to be the one big player on the block?

00:28:05.960 --> 00:28:12.080
[Guest]: I wouldn't categorize what's happening right now as bipolarity or a shift towards bipolarity.

00:28:12.080 --> 00:28:19.080
[Guest]: I think a lot of Chinese analysts would like to believe that bipolarity is inevitable.

00:28:19.080 --> 00:28:21.320
[Guest]: But I wouldn't categorize it as that right now.

00:28:21.320 --> 00:28:28.200
[Guest]: What I would say is that what's more inevitable is what's more probable, what's more inevitable,

00:28:28.200 --> 00:28:36.440
[Guest]: what's more probable is the idea of multipolarity with multiple power centers, whether it's

00:28:36.440 --> 00:28:43.080
[Guest]: the US, whether it's India, China, Russia, the European Union, probably South Africa,

00:28:43.080 --> 00:28:44.080
[Guest]: probably Brazil.

00:28:44.080 --> 00:28:50.320
[Guest]: So you have multiple power centers that will emerge, each with their own capacity to project

00:28:50.320 --> 00:28:55.920
[Guest]: power, whether it's economic, military power, hard power, soft power, economic.

00:28:55.920 --> 00:29:00.160
[Guest]: So that's how I would see, that's the way I see the world go, that's direction in which

00:29:00.160 --> 00:29:02.560
[Guest]: I see the world going in.

00:29:02.560 --> 00:29:07.000
[Guest]: And that would lead to some interesting combinations among states.

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:13.160
[Guest]: But as far as this notion that there would be bipolarity in the Chinese, the party is

00:29:13.160 --> 00:29:21.600
[Guest]: looking at this as an opportunity to somewhere replace the US as a leading global power eventually.

00:29:21.600 --> 00:29:25.960
[Guest]: You will see literature coming out of China which argues that, and which argues that is

00:29:25.960 --> 00:29:27.120
[Guest]: inevitable.

00:29:27.120 --> 00:29:32.980
[Guest]: But my sense is that if you just look at capacities at the moment, you will see that the Chinese

00:29:32.980 --> 00:29:39.840
[Guest]: don't necessarily have the hard power capacity to project power around the world, even in

00:29:39.840 --> 00:29:42.920
[Guest]: their region, which is East Asia.

00:29:42.920 --> 00:29:50.380
[Guest]: Their capacities are limited just by geography, just by US alliance systems.

00:29:50.380 --> 00:29:55.280
[Guest]: So there's a lot that needs to change for some of this bipolarity or any of this to

00:29:55.280 --> 00:29:56.720
[Guest]: come about.

00:29:56.720 --> 00:29:58.040
[Guest]: That's how I would view it.

00:29:58.040 --> 00:29:59.040
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:29:59.040 --> 00:30:04.480
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one of the dissonances I've always felt between economics and geopolitics,

00:30:04.480 --> 00:30:08.480
[Amit Varma]: and obviously, I know the former much better than I understand the latter, is that economics

00:30:08.480 --> 00:30:13.040
[Amit Varma]: is fundamentally positive somewhere, you know, two parties interact, and both of them can

00:30:13.040 --> 00:30:14.040
[Amit Varma]: benefit.

00:30:14.040 --> 00:30:19.720
[Amit Varma]: And geopolitics often plays out like a zero sum game, where, you know, there's a lot of

00:30:19.720 --> 00:30:22.840
[Amit Varma]: one upmanship, and there's a lot of zero sum thinking.

00:30:22.840 --> 00:30:27.400
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, with Trump becoming the president in the US, Trump is clearly a zero sum thinker.

00:30:27.400 --> 00:30:31.640
[Amit Varma]: I mean, that's the reason he started these trade wars, because he foolishly assumes that

00:30:31.640 --> 00:30:33.520
[Amit Varma]: a trade deficit is a bad thing.

00:30:33.520 --> 00:30:36.280
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, if there's a winner, there must be a loser.

00:30:36.280 --> 00:30:40.360
[Amit Varma]: And if there's a trade deficit, the US must be a loser, and so on and so forth.

00:30:40.360 --> 00:30:44.200
[Amit Varma]: And that's, that's obviously very fundamentally flawed thinking, but we can say that, okay,

00:30:44.200 --> 00:30:46.420
[Amit Varma]: Trump is an aberration.

00:30:46.420 --> 00:30:48.600
[Amit Varma]: But how does the Chinese view it?

00:30:48.600 --> 00:30:53.600
[Amit Varma]: Do they view it in positive some terms, in the sense that, look, we just need to expand

00:30:53.600 --> 00:30:57.680
[Amit Varma]: our trade everywhere, and everybody's benefiting, and that's fine, as long as, you know, we

00:30:57.680 --> 00:31:03.520
[Amit Varma]: are stronger, or do they also have a little bit of the zero sum sense where other people

00:31:03.520 --> 00:31:07.320
[Amit Varma]: have to be outwitted, and they have to establish their dominance?

00:31:07.320 --> 00:31:13.160
[Guest]: I think that the Chinese, if you look at the rhetoric, you will see the Chinese being very

00:31:13.160 --> 00:31:16.480
[Guest]: critical of the idea of zero sum politics.

00:31:16.480 --> 00:31:21.320
[Guest]: They will essentially repeatedly, if you look at Chinese diplomatic communication, they'll

00:31:21.320 --> 00:31:27.320
[Guest]: be talking about the fact that zero sum thinking is Cold War mentality, and the world has moved

00:31:27.320 --> 00:31:29.120
[Guest]: way past the Cold War.

00:31:29.120 --> 00:31:34.000
[Guest]: And we need to get beyond this, we need to look at win-win diplomacy, we need to look

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:39.400
[Guest]: at building a community of common destiny for all of mankind.

00:31:39.400 --> 00:31:43.640
[Guest]: All of this is fine rhetoric, but it doesn't necessarily translate into as idealistic a

00:31:43.640 --> 00:31:46.440
[Guest]: vision of the world in terms of practice.

00:31:46.440 --> 00:31:51.760
[Guest]: So in terms of practice, how the Chinese go about it is, fundamentally, my interests need

00:31:51.760 --> 00:31:54.080
[Guest]: to be taken care of.

00:31:54.080 --> 00:31:58.720
[Guest]: But yes, that does not necessarily mean that you need to be damaged, which is zero sum

00:31:58.720 --> 00:32:03.320
[Guest]: mentality, which is what Trump is doing when he's saying that our relationship is a transaction,

00:32:03.320 --> 00:32:05.240
[Guest]: I need to win every deal.

00:32:05.240 --> 00:32:10.240
[Guest]: The Chinese view it as, can I serve my interests while also getting you something that you

00:32:10.240 --> 00:32:13.240
[Guest]: want, which is their approach in Africa.

00:32:13.240 --> 00:32:18.960
[Guest]: And just an example of that approach I'll give you, last week when Xi Jinping was in

00:32:18.960 --> 00:32:25.200
[Guest]: Africa and when he visited Rwanda, there was a quote by the president of Rwanda, Paul Kagame,

00:32:25.200 --> 00:32:30.360
[Guest]: where he talks about how China relates to Africa as an equal.

00:32:30.360 --> 00:32:34.440
[Guest]: He says, we see ourselves as people on the road to prosperity.

00:32:34.440 --> 00:32:37.720
[Guest]: China's actions demonstrate that you see us the same way.

00:32:37.720 --> 00:32:43.080
[Guest]: This is a revolutionary posture in world affairs, and it is much more important, much more precious

00:32:43.080 --> 00:32:44.520
[Guest]: than money.

00:32:44.520 --> 00:32:49.360
[Guest]: So you can see that there is an approach with China, which is not necessarily zero sum.

00:32:49.360 --> 00:32:54.480
[Guest]: It's willing to play the game, it's willing to bargain, it's willing to trade off, provided

00:32:54.480 --> 00:32:57.160
[Guest]: that its core interests are met.

00:32:57.160 --> 00:33:00.800
[Guest]: And that's something that America under Trump is not doing so well.

00:33:00.800 --> 00:33:04.440
[Guest]: So that's how I would characterize China's approach, which is that I have a certain set

00:33:04.440 --> 00:33:09.320
[Guest]: of core interests, any engagement needs to make sure that those core interests are met.

00:33:09.320 --> 00:33:13.640
[Guest]: Within those boundaries, I can work with you.

00:33:13.640 --> 00:33:15.600
[Amit Varma]: And that actually sounds eminently sensible.

00:33:15.600 --> 00:33:20.960
[Amit Varma]: And so I'm going to ask you to sort of take a step back from description to prescription,

00:33:20.960 --> 00:33:26.480
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that if you then have to look at China's foreign policy as an expert, what

00:33:26.480 --> 00:33:27.980
[Amit Varma]: would you do differently?

00:33:27.980 --> 00:33:30.280
[Amit Varma]: Is there any reason for the approach to be different?

00:33:30.280 --> 00:33:33.600
[Amit Varma]: Or does this all make spectacularly good sense to you?

00:33:33.600 --> 00:33:35.280
[Guest]: I think it makes really good sense.

00:33:35.280 --> 00:33:36.760
[Guest]: I think it makes really good sense.

00:33:36.760 --> 00:33:43.320
[Guest]: I think the errors that the Chinese have made in the last few years have been this error

00:33:43.320 --> 00:33:50.200
[Guest]: of assertion, this error of announcing themselves as a great power, as a big power, before they

00:33:50.200 --> 00:33:55.520
[Guest]: actually have got the kind of capacity that you need to be a great or a big power.

00:33:55.520 --> 00:33:59.800
[Guest]: And you can see that manifesting in how the Chinese are now looking at scaling down some

00:33:59.800 --> 00:34:04.520
[Guest]: of their rhetoric about, oh, we are not that innovative, we are not that technologically

00:34:04.520 --> 00:34:06.400
[Guest]: advanced.

00:34:06.400 --> 00:34:09.200
[Guest]: So that rhetorical shift is what they are making.

00:34:09.200 --> 00:34:13.800
[Guest]: Because this announcement of China being this great power, which is going to play this leading

00:34:13.800 --> 00:34:18.840
[Guest]: role in world affairs, which is once again wants to take the center stage in world affairs,

00:34:18.840 --> 00:34:24.200
[Guest]: leaves you open to a lot of criticism about your domestic economy being highly shielded,

00:34:24.200 --> 00:34:29.480
[Guest]: about access to your markets, about the problems that your investments are creating in other

00:34:29.480 --> 00:34:30.480
[Guest]: countries.

00:34:30.480 --> 00:34:33.880
[Guest]: So I think rhetorically, those are the errors that they have made.

00:34:33.880 --> 00:34:38.680
[Guest]: Practically, what they need to do is they need to look at their own.

00:34:38.680 --> 00:34:42.680
[Guest]: If I was a Chinese analyst, if I was sitting in Beijing, what I would be advising the government

00:34:42.680 --> 00:34:49.120
[Guest]: is that we need to fundamentally look at our debt issues, because our economy is perched

00:34:49.120 --> 00:34:55.200
[Guest]: on a massive debt overhang, which we've been kicking this can down the road year after

00:34:55.200 --> 00:34:56.200
[Guest]: year.

00:34:56.200 --> 00:34:59.720
[Guest]: Sooner or later, it's something that's going to come to bite.

00:34:59.720 --> 00:35:03.660
[Guest]: And this will damage us not just domestically, but also internationally.

00:35:03.660 --> 00:35:09.080
[Guest]: What happens to you when all these pledges of belt and road investments that you've made

00:35:09.080 --> 00:35:14.180
[Guest]: are no longer doable because you're struggling with debt at home?

00:35:14.180 --> 00:35:19.960
[Guest]: It completely undermines the idea of China as this pillar on which a new sort of global

00:35:19.960 --> 00:35:21.920
[Guest]: economy can be built.

00:35:21.920 --> 00:35:26.680
[Guest]: So I'd somewhere pull back on the rhetoric.

00:35:26.680 --> 00:35:31.760
[Guest]: And I'd also try and look at structural issues domestically.

00:35:31.760 --> 00:35:37.880
[Guest]: The things that the Chinese have done right in the last few months or a year or so, is

00:35:37.880 --> 00:35:43.760
[Guest]: that they've looked to soften their positions with regard to Japan, India.

00:35:43.760 --> 00:35:49.400
[Guest]: And despite all the conflict and confrontation with the Australians over issues of sharp

00:35:49.400 --> 00:35:55.120
[Guest]: power and Chinese influence in domestic Australian politics, they have shown overtures where

00:35:55.120 --> 00:35:57.720
[Guest]: they would like the Australians to work with them.

00:35:57.720 --> 00:36:02.920
[Guest]: So they've identified that there is a potential for countries to coalesce against us.

00:36:02.920 --> 00:36:09.400
[Guest]: And that's, again, a product of their policies, tangible policies in the South China Sea,

00:36:09.400 --> 00:36:14.240
[Guest]: but also a product of their rhetorical approach, which has been one of China has arrived and

00:36:14.240 --> 00:36:17.240
[Guest]: China will do what it wants to do.

00:36:17.240 --> 00:36:22.800
[Guest]: And so the scaling down of the rhetoric, the reaching out to Japan, reaching out to India,

00:36:22.800 --> 00:36:27.680
[Guest]: reaching out to Australia, looking to work with multiple actors, even though there are

00:36:27.680 --> 00:36:32.760
[Guest]: political shifts in different countries, say Malaysia, which has just had an election.

00:36:32.760 --> 00:36:37.440
[Guest]: And the new leadership has blocked Chinese projects, but the Chinese haven't gone sour

00:36:37.440 --> 00:36:38.440
[Guest]: on them.

00:36:38.440 --> 00:36:39.600
[Guest]: They've in fact reached out to them.

00:36:39.600 --> 00:36:43.000
[Guest]: The Chinese foreign minister was one of the first foreign ministers to travel and have

00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:45.880
[Guest]: a conversation with the Malaysians.

00:36:45.880 --> 00:36:50.000
[Guest]: And it's quite likely that Mahathir Mohamad, the prime minister, would be visiting Beijing

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:51.580
[Guest]: soon this month.

00:36:51.580 --> 00:36:55.920
[Guest]: So you can see that the Chinese are looking at deeper engagement and softening their positions.

00:36:55.920 --> 00:37:01.160
[Guest]: And I think the biggest sort of giveaway that this is going to happen more in the coming

00:37:01.160 --> 00:37:06.960
[Guest]: future is in the end of June, there was a Central Foreign Affairs Work Conference held

00:37:06.960 --> 00:37:08.880
[Guest]: in Beijing.

00:37:08.880 --> 00:37:12.480
[Guest]: And Central Foreign Affairs Work Conference essentially is a conference where all the

00:37:12.480 --> 00:37:17.540
[Guest]: senior most delegates of this party meet together and they debate, deliberate on foreign policy

00:37:17.540 --> 00:37:20.720
[Guest]: and the agenda and how they should go about it.

00:37:20.720 --> 00:37:24.640
[Guest]: And this is just the second time that such a conference has happened in Xi Jinping's

00:37:24.640 --> 00:37:26.720
[Guest]: tenure so far.

00:37:26.720 --> 00:37:32.120
[Guest]: And during this conference, they came up with a list of 10 points which characterize Xi

00:37:32.120 --> 00:37:34.680
[Guest]: Jinping's thought on diplomacy.

00:37:34.680 --> 00:37:41.680
[Guest]: And the point of core interest was number nine, which indicates that they want to downgrade

00:37:41.680 --> 00:37:43.560
[Guest]: a certain, their assertion.

00:37:43.560 --> 00:37:49.320
[Guest]: They want to make sure that this assertive attitude is not that significant going forward.

00:37:49.320 --> 00:37:54.200
[Guest]: And what was on the top, what was among the priority list was this idea of working with

00:37:54.200 --> 00:37:57.780
[Guest]: countries, creating a shared community of common destiny.

00:37:57.780 --> 00:38:03.180
[Guest]: So all that signifies that you're going to be looking to reaching out to countries.

00:38:03.180 --> 00:38:09.000
[Guest]: You want to build partnerships because things around you are changing quite dramatically,

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:11.300
[Guest]: largely owing to Trump.

00:38:11.300 --> 00:38:16.600
[Guest]: And so this is, I think they've adopted the right path, but it's just about have you gone

00:38:16.600 --> 00:38:17.600
[Guest]: too far?

00:38:17.600 --> 00:38:21.920
[Guest]: If you let the cat out of the bag already, can you put the genie back in the bottle?

00:38:21.920 --> 00:38:25.520
[Guest]: I think that's the balance that the Chinese government needs to strike right now.

00:38:25.520 --> 00:38:28.000
[Amit Varma]: So I'm going to ask you about the implications in this for India.

00:38:28.000 --> 00:38:32.480
[Amit Varma]: But before we go there, I was intrigued by the debt crisis that you mentioned and the

00:38:32.480 --> 00:38:34.400
[Amit Varma]: fact that they need to do something about it.

00:38:34.400 --> 00:38:39.040
[Amit Varma]: So give me a sense of what that debt crisis is, what is the worst case scenario in which

00:38:39.040 --> 00:38:40.600
[Amit Varma]: it plays out?

00:38:40.600 --> 00:38:45.560
[Amit Varma]: And what is it you would recommend that they do now to, you know, before things get worse?

00:38:45.560 --> 00:38:49.760
[Guest]: OK, so I should preface this by saying that I'm not an economist and I know very little

00:38:49.760 --> 00:38:54.680
[Guest]: about how economies function, but here's my broad sense.

00:38:54.680 --> 00:38:58.200
[Guest]: So why did the Chinese accumulate all this debt?

00:38:58.200 --> 00:39:03.400
[Guest]: They accumulated all this debt is because they wanted to invest heavily at a point of

00:39:03.400 --> 00:39:04.400
[Guest]: time.

00:39:04.400 --> 00:39:07.760
[Guest]: I'm going to go back to say about 2008 again, because again, that is one of those tipping

00:39:07.760 --> 00:39:10.800
[Guest]: points where all this begins to happen.

00:39:10.800 --> 00:39:16.120
[Guest]: So in 2008, once the world economy is going through this cash crunch, this liquidity crunch,

00:39:16.120 --> 00:39:20.600
[Guest]: the People's Bank, the Chinese Central Bank, announces a massive stimulus package.

00:39:20.600 --> 00:39:27.920
[Guest]: I can't remember the numbers, but it's hundreds of billions of dollars, a stimulus package

00:39:27.920 --> 00:39:29.800
[Guest]: for the economy.

00:39:29.800 --> 00:39:36.800
[Guest]: And they hope that by stimulating investment, then you can create growth.

00:39:36.800 --> 00:39:37.800
[Guest]: And that's what they do.

00:39:37.800 --> 00:39:43.080
[Guest]: You have more and more states and provinces and local governments undertaking massive

00:39:43.080 --> 00:39:48.360
[Guest]: infrastructure projects because there is all this cash now available.

00:39:48.360 --> 00:39:53.040
[Guest]: And all these infrastructure projects, you're not considering necessarily the economic viability

00:39:53.040 --> 00:39:54.040
[Guest]: of these projects.

00:39:54.040 --> 00:39:57.080
[Guest]: I mean, are they going to lead to any productivity gain?

00:39:57.080 --> 00:40:01.600
[Guest]: You're investing because that looks good on your GDP because you're constructing.

00:40:01.600 --> 00:40:06.160
[Guest]: And that's how growth continues for a significant amount of time.

00:40:06.160 --> 00:40:10.120
[Guest]: Throughout that period of time, the Chinese government is talking about wanting to shift

00:40:10.120 --> 00:40:15.800
[Guest]: from export and investment driven growth to consumption driven growth.

00:40:15.800 --> 00:40:20.320
[Guest]: Now, we've got a domestic market, we need to stimulate consumption and investments are

00:40:20.320 --> 00:40:22.160
[Guest]: being wasteful to a large degree.

00:40:22.160 --> 00:40:25.180
[Guest]: So we need to curtail this wasteful investment.

00:40:25.180 --> 00:40:30.280
[Guest]: So what starts to happen is that because the government at the center, somewhere it wants

00:40:30.280 --> 00:40:34.320
[Guest]: to contain this investment, but it also needs to sustain growth.

00:40:34.320 --> 00:40:38.480
[Guest]: So there is this push and pull which is going on, during which period of time, a lot of

00:40:38.480 --> 00:40:44.000
[Guest]: local governments, a lot of companies are piling on massive amounts of debt.

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:48.560
[Guest]: Because at the end of the day, for a local mayor like me, if I'm the mayor of a city

00:40:48.560 --> 00:40:54.760
[Guest]: like Tianjin, bureaucratically, my progression up the ladder in the Chinese system is dependent

00:40:54.760 --> 00:40:56.920
[Guest]: on how I deliver on these material goals.

00:40:56.920 --> 00:41:01.800
[Guest]: And if I'm supposed to meet 9% growth, 10% growth, I will take on the debt to meet that

00:41:01.800 --> 00:41:02.800
[Guest]: growth.

00:41:02.800 --> 00:41:06.680
[Guest]: And eventually those massive projects, whether it is a metro project or a massive park or

00:41:06.680 --> 00:41:11.160
[Guest]: a massive housing system, that's going to be looked after by somebody else.

00:41:11.160 --> 00:41:14.200
[Guest]: Because in a couple of years time, I'm going to move on to a different job.

00:41:14.200 --> 00:41:17.140
[Guest]: So this is somebody else's problem who comes after me.

00:41:17.140 --> 00:41:22.820
[Guest]: So that's how the system has piled on this massive amounts of debt largely.

00:41:22.820 --> 00:41:27.120
[Guest]: At present, Xi Jinping has been talking about deleveraging for the last few years.

00:41:27.120 --> 00:41:31.320
[Guest]: He wants, he realizes that there's a lot of unnecessary debt that's been picked up, whether

00:41:31.320 --> 00:41:36.800
[Guest]: it's in infrastructure, whether it's in things called zombie companies, which are essentially

00:41:36.800 --> 00:41:40.960
[Guest]: companies which are no longer profitable, but are propped up by state subsidies.

00:41:40.960 --> 00:41:43.360
[Guest]: And he wants to curtail all of this.

00:41:43.360 --> 00:41:45.800
[Guest]: He wants to rein in this level of debt.

00:41:45.800 --> 00:41:52.880
[Guest]: But the problem is that the more you strip the cash flow in the economy, it's not just

00:41:52.880 --> 00:41:53.880
[Guest]: going to slow down.

00:41:53.880 --> 00:41:57.600
[Guest]: It's also going to lead to companies shutting down, job losses, and that's going to lead

00:41:57.600 --> 00:41:59.360
[Guest]: to instability.

00:41:59.360 --> 00:42:05.720
[Guest]: So how do you balance that push and pull between stability, growth, and wanting to have more

00:42:05.720 --> 00:42:07.400
[Guest]: productive growth?

00:42:07.400 --> 00:42:11.160
[Guest]: So that's broadly the nature of the beast at the moment.

00:42:11.160 --> 00:42:12.160
[Amit Varma]: That's incredibly fascinating.

00:42:12.160 --> 00:42:17.480
[Amit Varma]: And it sounds to me very similar to how the US financial crisis happened in terms of it

00:42:17.480 --> 00:42:21.120
[Amit Varma]: being enabled by easy money and bad incentives.

00:42:21.120 --> 00:42:26.600
[Amit Varma]: But you know, moving on from the economics and back to the foreign policy, India's always

00:42:26.600 --> 00:42:29.040
[Amit Varma]: had a sort of an iffy relationship with China.

00:42:29.040 --> 00:42:33.880
[Amit Varma]: We've lost a war to them, we've kind of, you know, been wary of them, we have an ongoing

00:42:33.880 --> 00:42:35.640
[Amit Varma]: border dispute with them.

00:42:35.640 --> 00:42:41.160
[Amit Varma]: How does or how does China's new approach to its place in the world affect India?

00:42:41.160 --> 00:42:46.320
[Guest]: You know, I want to answer this question with an anecdote to begin with.

00:42:46.320 --> 00:42:49.840
[Guest]: So I spent five years living in the mainland.

00:42:49.840 --> 00:42:57.280
[Guest]: And in those five years, anybody that I spoke to, whether it was from the media, or it was

00:42:57.280 --> 00:43:03.560
[Guest]: from, you know, the ordinary sort of intelligentsia, the ordinary public, factory people, people

00:43:03.560 --> 00:43:08.760
[Guest]: who are in manufacturing and across the sector, I found only a handful of people perhaps who

00:43:08.760 --> 00:43:13.640
[Guest]: knew that there had been a war between India and China.

00:43:13.640 --> 00:43:19.320
[Guest]: It's not something that they've, it's not something that survived in public memory.

00:43:19.320 --> 00:43:22.920
[Guest]: And that's probably because the party has not wanted it to survive as much.

00:43:22.920 --> 00:43:27.360
[Guest]: Today, obviously, things are different, and that's because of the Doklam standoff last

00:43:27.360 --> 00:43:35.160
[Guest]: year, where you had Chinese media being extremely critical of India, you had a lot of racist

00:43:35.160 --> 00:43:44.400
[Guest]: content, you had content which called out India, which put out editorials from 1962.

00:43:44.400 --> 00:43:48.640
[Guest]: So the war essentially is now back in the memory, at least in public consciousness,

00:43:48.640 --> 00:43:52.600
[Guest]: I presume people would know because I got a lot of messages from friends in China at

00:43:52.600 --> 00:43:58.080
[Guest]: that point of time, saying that, oh, we didn't realize that this had happened, and that we

00:43:58.080 --> 00:44:02.680
[Guest]: had a war in the past, and we hope that there's no more war in the future.

00:44:02.680 --> 00:44:08.040
[Guest]: So that's just an aside, an anecdote, that a lot of people in India, I mean, in India,

00:44:08.040 --> 00:44:12.120
[Guest]: the war with China is so deep in within our conscience.

00:44:12.120 --> 00:44:13.800
[Guest]: But I don't think that's the same over there.

00:44:13.800 --> 00:44:21.000
[Guest]: It doesn't resonate similarly, in terms of how China sees India today, and what China's

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:25.760
[Guest]: new position in the world implies for India.

00:44:25.760 --> 00:44:36.160
[Guest]: So I think we can take what happened in Wuhan, as an example of China recognizing that India

00:44:36.160 --> 00:44:38.360
[Guest]: is an important actor.

00:44:38.360 --> 00:44:44.600
[Guest]: I think we've seen this for the last two years, when India boycotted the Belt and Road Forum

00:44:44.600 --> 00:44:53.240
[Guest]: in 2016, you saw that when we boycotted the Belt and Road Forum, there was a lot of talk

00:44:53.240 --> 00:44:57.680
[Guest]: about India being the only country which had not attended this forum.

00:44:57.680 --> 00:45:01.000
[Guest]: And there was some degree of frustration from the Chinese point of view.

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:06.480
[Guest]: But there was repeated attempt to try and get India on board by talking about CPEC being

00:45:06.480 --> 00:45:11.320
[Guest]: a development initiative, and China's position on Kashmir does not change, and so on and

00:45:11.320 --> 00:45:13.420
[Guest]: so forth.

00:45:13.420 --> 00:45:19.720
[Guest]: And thereafter, after the Doklam standoff, this accommodation by both parties, which

00:45:19.720 --> 00:45:26.520
[Guest]: began at the meeting in Xiamen and BRICS in September last year, and then has further

00:45:26.520 --> 00:45:33.440
[Guest]: gone on to Wuhan and thereafter, I think the Chinese see value in working with India.

00:45:33.440 --> 00:45:36.480
[Guest]: They know that India is geographically well placed.

00:45:36.480 --> 00:45:42.120
[Guest]: If Belt and Road in South Asia has to yield some degree of success, a measure of success

00:45:42.120 --> 00:45:44.440
[Guest]: in India, you need to get India on board.

00:45:44.440 --> 00:45:51.360
[Guest]: India is also a massive market for infrastructure investment, for Chinese companies to set up

00:45:51.360 --> 00:45:56.160
[Guest]: manufacturing bases, there's lots that the Chinese can do in India.

00:45:56.160 --> 00:46:00.160
[Guest]: And so I think that there is a sense that India can be a partner.

00:46:00.160 --> 00:46:07.520
[Guest]: But along with that, there is also this suspicion that persists with regards to India's relationship

00:46:07.520 --> 00:46:08.520
[Guest]: with the West.

00:46:08.520 --> 00:46:13.600
[Guest]: Again, I don't think that the Chinese see the world necessarily as a zero-sum game,

00:46:13.600 --> 00:46:20.420
[Guest]: but they are fundamentally cautious about the idea of India, the US, Australia, Japan,

00:46:20.420 --> 00:46:25.200
[Guest]: this idea of these democracies coalescing together to contain China.

00:46:25.200 --> 00:46:32.560
[Guest]: So they see India as a possible spoke in the US alliance network, the US alliance wheel,

00:46:32.560 --> 00:46:35.760
[Guest]: and they see that as a possible occurrence.

00:46:35.760 --> 00:46:40.560
[Guest]: So therefore, I feel that there is this sense of that we need to engage with India.

00:46:40.560 --> 00:46:45.200
[Guest]: And Wuhan was that example where there was, it was not just the Indian side which wanted

00:46:45.200 --> 00:46:50.560
[Guest]: to engage, but it was also the Chinese who wanted to engage and who saw merit in working

00:46:50.560 --> 00:46:51.560
[Guest]: together.

00:46:51.560 --> 00:46:55.400
[Guest]: So I feel that there is actually opportunities going forward.

00:46:55.400 --> 00:46:59.560
[Amit Varma]: So can you explain Wuhan to me because I don't know much about what happened there.

00:46:59.560 --> 00:47:05.380
[Guest]: Okay, so this was basically, it came as a bit of a surprise.

00:47:05.380 --> 00:47:08.800
[Guest]: So Narendra Modi, after the Doklam standoff, Prime Minister Narendra Modi, Indian Prime

00:47:08.800 --> 00:47:14.440
[Guest]: Minister, he traveled to Xiamen in September last year, which is a city in Southeast China.

00:47:14.440 --> 00:47:17.680
[Guest]: He traveled over there for the BRICS summit.

00:47:17.680 --> 00:47:23.320
[Guest]: At that summit, from what we understand, there was a, there was sort of a breaking of the

00:47:23.320 --> 00:47:31.400
[Guest]: ice and Xi Jinping and Modi spoke and there was feelers put out of having a broader conversation

00:47:31.400 --> 00:47:36.280
[Guest]: that led to more diplomatic activity with the Chinese foreign minister visiting New

00:47:36.280 --> 00:47:41.880
[Guest]: Delhi in December and talks again, beginning on the boundary issue.

00:47:41.880 --> 00:47:45.760
[Guest]: And that graduated in February this year, we had Foreign Secretary Vijay Gokhale go

00:47:45.760 --> 00:47:51.880
[Guest]: to China and that set up again a framework of what sort of conversation we need to have.

00:47:51.880 --> 00:47:58.200
[Guest]: And that essentially led to this meeting in Wuhan between Xi Jinping and Narendra Modi.

00:47:58.200 --> 00:48:03.240
[Guest]: And the idea was that it's a two day summit, it's informal, it's unstructured, we're not

00:48:03.240 --> 00:48:09.080
[Guest]: necessarily going to be talking about specific issues and identifying specific outcomes that

00:48:09.080 --> 00:48:10.080
[Guest]: we need to come up with.

00:48:10.080 --> 00:48:14.720
[Guest]: We're going to have this broad based conversation about what are your interests?

00:48:14.720 --> 00:48:15.720
[Guest]: What are our interests?

00:48:15.720 --> 00:48:17.280
[Guest]: How can we work together?

00:48:17.280 --> 00:48:22.040
[Guest]: How can we prevent potential conflict like situations erupting?

00:48:22.040 --> 00:48:27.160
[Guest]: Because last year at Doklam, we ended up in a position where there was a lot of talk of

00:48:27.160 --> 00:48:32.200
[Guest]: war and there was a lot of jingoism, largely from the Chinese side, actually, the Indian

00:48:32.200 --> 00:48:34.600
[Guest]: side was very restrained.

00:48:34.600 --> 00:48:40.080
[Guest]: So Wuhan was this opportunity for these two leaders to sit down together and say, look,

00:48:40.080 --> 00:48:43.340
[Guest]: there are dramatic changes happening in the world.

00:48:43.340 --> 00:48:48.640
[Guest]: At the end of the day, we're neighbors, we're growing economies, we have converging interests,

00:48:48.640 --> 00:48:52.080
[Guest]: and we need to engage, we can't end up in some of these binaries.

00:48:52.080 --> 00:48:57.240
[Guest]: That's the broad narrative that's been put out by both sides.

00:48:57.240 --> 00:49:01.560
[Guest]: And since then, we've seen deeper engagement between the two countries.

00:49:01.560 --> 00:49:07.080
[Guest]: What I mean by deeper engagement is that they're going to resume bilateral military exercises

00:49:07.080 --> 00:49:11.560
[Guest]: this year, India will be participating in the Shanghai Cooperation Organization's military

00:49:11.560 --> 00:49:18.320
[Guest]: exercises along with China and Pakistan, India has been probably a little more restrained

00:49:18.320 --> 00:49:22.400
[Guest]: in terms of its criticism of Belt and Road.

00:49:22.400 --> 00:49:26.240
[Guest]: There are some analysts who would say that India has also scaled down its activity with

00:49:26.240 --> 00:49:30.520
[Guest]: the quadrilateral group, which is the US, Australia, Japan and India.

00:49:30.520 --> 00:49:33.000
[Guest]: I don't necessarily subscribe to that.

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:38.360
[Guest]: But yeah, you can see that in terms of public rhetoric, there has been a general shift in

00:49:38.360 --> 00:49:44.200
[Guest]: India's position where we're not necessarily being that critical, while we are keeping

00:49:44.200 --> 00:49:51.760
[Guest]: our fundamental oppositions to BRI, whether it be with related to CPEC or debt, still

00:49:51.760 --> 00:49:52.760
[Guest]: out there.

00:49:52.760 --> 00:49:58.440
[Guest]: But we're not necessarily going out proselytizing or telling people that this is a real problem.

00:49:58.440 --> 00:50:01.800
[Guest]: So I think there's a broad understanding that's been arrived at between the two sides that

00:50:01.800 --> 00:50:05.720
[Guest]: we need to maintain peace at the border, we need to look at our common interests, and

00:50:05.720 --> 00:50:08.000
[Guest]: we need to work on them.

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:14.480
[Guest]: One of the tangible outcomes of that Wuhan meeting was this idea that India does not

00:50:14.480 --> 00:50:21.520
[Guest]: need to look at China's engagement within South Asia with a lens of suspicion.

00:50:21.520 --> 00:50:29.320
[Guest]: So the Chinese have proposed this model called India-China Plus or India-China X, under which

00:50:29.320 --> 00:50:34.080
[Guest]: they want India and China to work together in a third country, carry out joint projects

00:50:34.080 --> 00:50:35.680
[Guest]: in a third country.

00:50:35.680 --> 00:50:39.640
[Guest]: And the first country that they've announced for this is Afghanistan.

00:50:39.640 --> 00:50:42.960
[Guest]: It's still not clear what exactly this joint project will be.

00:50:42.960 --> 00:50:47.640
[Guest]: But what we know as of now is that there will be a joint capacity building project.

00:50:47.640 --> 00:50:51.960
[Guest]: We're not still clear on the details of when that will happen, what that project is going

00:50:51.960 --> 00:50:53.080
[Guest]: to be.

00:50:53.080 --> 00:50:58.240
[Guest]: But the idea is you've set about a framework of working together as opposed to looking

00:50:58.240 --> 00:51:01.360
[Guest]: at each other's actions with suspicion.

00:51:01.360 --> 00:51:02.360
[Amit Varma]: All of that is very heartening.

00:51:02.360 --> 00:51:07.280
[Amit Varma]: But I want to go back to a phrase you used a little earlier when you spoke about China's

00:51:07.280 --> 00:51:10.720
[Amit Varma]: attitude to China's position on Kashmir.

00:51:10.720 --> 00:51:16.760
[Amit Varma]: And you know, there's also been the sense that China is sort of exploring deeper engagement

00:51:16.760 --> 00:51:20.960
[Amit Varma]: with Pakistan and helping them in their conflict with us.

00:51:20.960 --> 00:51:26.680
[Amit Varma]: Now, is that sort of a historical artifact of how the world used to be a while ago, or

00:51:26.680 --> 00:51:27.680
[Guest]: are they hedging?

00:51:27.680 --> 00:51:30.280
[Guest]: Okay, so that's a good question.

00:51:30.280 --> 00:51:36.200
[Guest]: I would see the China-Pakistan relationship, yes, of course, it has implications for India,

00:51:36.200 --> 00:51:40.680
[Guest]: but I would see it also as independent of India.

00:51:40.680 --> 00:51:43.760
[Guest]: The China-Pakistan relationship is very deep.

00:51:43.760 --> 00:51:50.480
[Guest]: It's deep political engagement, it's deep economic engagement, it's deep military engagement.

00:51:50.480 --> 00:51:55.440
[Guest]: There is a strategic relationship between these two sides, and which at some level has

00:51:55.440 --> 00:51:59.920
[Guest]: implications for India, serious implications for India, but it's also independent.

00:51:59.920 --> 00:52:04.520
[Guest]: So CPEC is an example of how it's independent of India.

00:52:04.520 --> 00:52:10.560
[Guest]: I personally don't see CPEC as something that is targeted at India.

00:52:10.560 --> 00:52:15.600
[Guest]: The Chinese could have managed CPEC better, the routing particularly, and they could have

00:52:15.600 --> 00:52:17.280
[Amit Varma]: managed to avoid some of these.

00:52:17.280 --> 00:52:19.720
[Amit Varma]: Just expand on what CPEC is.

00:52:19.720 --> 00:52:24.880
[Guest]: So CPEC is the China-Pakistan Economic Corridor, which is this massive corridor which begins

00:52:24.880 --> 00:52:31.240
[Guest]: in Xinjiang in China, and goes all the way down to Gwadar in Pakistan.

00:52:31.240 --> 00:52:40.000
[Guest]: This is going to be Chinese investments in building roads, bridges, rail networks, ports,

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:41.840
[Guest]: free trade zones.

00:52:41.840 --> 00:52:46.480
[Guest]: So it's part of the broader Belt and Road Strategy.

00:52:46.480 --> 00:52:53.240
[Guest]: As far as we know, the pledged investment is around $60 billion, and CPEC should be

00:52:53.240 --> 00:52:57.260
[Guest]: completed, the time range for this is till 2030.

00:52:57.260 --> 00:53:03.560
[Guest]: So it's over a period of 14-15 years is when the Chinese see this as being completed.

00:53:03.560 --> 00:53:07.720
[Guest]: So the idea is to essentially support the Pakistanis in terms of building all this infrastructure

00:53:07.720 --> 00:53:13.480
[Guest]: and facilities for them, and also gain, sort of deepen their own economic footprint within

00:53:13.480 --> 00:53:15.480
[Guest]: Pakistan.

00:53:15.480 --> 00:53:21.600
[Guest]: So the India component of this obviously comes from the fact that part of the CPEC route

00:53:21.600 --> 00:53:26.880
[Guest]: runs through what is Pakistani-occupied Kashmir.

00:53:26.880 --> 00:53:32.280
[Guest]: And so that's where India's objections primarily are that, well, this is impinging on our sovereignty

00:53:32.280 --> 00:53:36.720
[Guest]: because all of Kashmir is an integral part of India.

00:53:36.720 --> 00:53:41.160
[Guest]: And the Chinese say, well, look, don't look at this as a political issue, this is purely

00:53:41.160 --> 00:53:49.600
[Guest]: a development project, which is, I mean, that's an argument that has weak legs to stand on.

00:53:49.600 --> 00:53:53.840
[Guest]: I mean, the Chinese would not allow anybody else to build in an area that they claim as

00:53:53.840 --> 00:53:57.440
[Guest]: theirs, but take it for what it is.

00:53:57.440 --> 00:53:59.360
[Guest]: So that's what CPEC is.

00:53:59.360 --> 00:54:05.560
[Guest]: So I would say the Pakistani-Chinese relationship is far broader because today, Pakistan, if

00:54:05.560 --> 00:54:10.360
[Guest]: you look at Pakistani politics today in the state of the army, Pakistan's fracture of

00:54:10.360 --> 00:54:17.080
[Guest]: its relationship with the US, China has become an important patron for the Pakistanis.

00:54:17.080 --> 00:54:21.760
[Guest]: It's always been an important partner, but today it's become a patron.

00:54:21.760 --> 00:54:23.880
[Guest]: So that's how I would classify that.

00:54:23.880 --> 00:54:31.200
[Guest]: Now what deeper Chinese engagement with Pakistan does is that it also raises the stakes for

00:54:31.200 --> 00:54:37.800
[Guest]: China to ensure stability in Pakistan and also stability between India and Pakistan.

00:54:37.800 --> 00:54:42.320
[Guest]: So there's an interesting dynamic that comes into play where China now becomes an actor

00:54:42.320 --> 00:54:51.360
[Guest]: that has legitimate interest in averting conflict between these two rival states in some way.

00:54:51.360 --> 00:54:56.440
[Guest]: So to me, that's the concept, that's the idea that's interesting in all of this, is that

00:54:56.440 --> 00:55:01.440
[Guest]: it raises China's stakes to ensure stability.

00:55:01.440 --> 00:55:07.960
[Guest]: And if China does gain the kind of leverage that we imagine that it has, that Indians

00:55:07.960 --> 00:55:13.400
[Guest]: imagine that it has, that China has deep say in Pakistan, it actually can motivate policy

00:55:13.400 --> 00:55:16.720
[Guest]: in Pakistan, I doubt all of that.

00:55:16.720 --> 00:55:22.940
[Guest]: But if the stakes get higher and the Chinese can develop levers and drivers to at least

00:55:22.940 --> 00:55:30.080
[Guest]: shape policies in Pakistan, that can have massive implications for India and probably

00:55:30.080 --> 00:55:31.640
[Guest]: even positive implications.

00:55:31.640 --> 00:55:34.560
[Amit Varma]: No, and positive implications, exactly.

00:55:34.560 --> 00:55:39.480
[Amit Varma]: Because just thinking aloud, you know, a couple of episodes back, your colleague Pranay Kotesane

00:55:39.480 --> 00:55:45.000
[Amit Varma]: had done an episode with me on Pakistan, where he spoke about how there are basically two

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:46.000
[Amit Varma]: Pakistan's.

00:55:46.000 --> 00:55:49.160
[Amit Varma]: One is the military jihadi complex, which rules Pakistan and the other is basically

00:55:49.160 --> 00:55:54.240
[Amit Varma]: the putative state of Pakistan, or you could say, the people of Pakistan, the civil society

00:55:54.240 --> 00:55:59.840
[Amit Varma]: of Pakistan and economic development of the kind that China is clearly hoping to enable

00:55:59.840 --> 00:56:04.880
[Amit Varma]: there would strengthen civil society vis-a-vis the military jihadi complex.

00:56:04.880 --> 00:56:11.040
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, it would increase the incentives of the military jihadi complex

00:56:11.040 --> 00:56:16.240
[Amit Varma]: to sort of keep Pakistan stable and not enter into a conflict with India.

00:56:16.240 --> 00:56:23.080
[Amit Varma]: So yeah, I mean, in that sense, a deepening Chinese involvement in Pakistan is something

00:56:23.080 --> 00:56:27.240
[Amit Varma]: that could actually turn out pretty well for us contrary to rhetoric.

00:56:27.240 --> 00:56:32.360
[Amit Varma]: I've taken a lot of your time, I want to end by asking you a dual question that I ask all

00:56:32.360 --> 00:56:39.280
[Amit Varma]: my guests on whatever the subject of the expertise is, that what makes you hopeful?

00:56:39.280 --> 00:56:46.040
[Amit Varma]: And what makes you anxious about China's new direction in foreign policy?

00:56:46.040 --> 00:56:50.160
[Guest]: Okay, what makes me hopeful is the, that's a good question.

00:56:50.160 --> 00:56:55.680
[Guest]: What makes me hopeful is the idea that there is a desire now, there has been reflection,

00:56:55.680 --> 00:56:59.520
[Guest]: at least it appears so, that there has been some reflection and there has been a desire

00:56:59.520 --> 00:57:03.760
[Guest]: to recast Chinese foreign policy as less aggressive.

00:57:03.760 --> 00:57:08.840
[Guest]: And the pressures that have come with this trade war have meant that there has been a

00:57:08.840 --> 00:57:14.200
[Guest]: certain degree of rethink and a certain degree of imperative to actually open up China further.

00:57:14.200 --> 00:57:20.920
[Guest]: So there is hope that as China engages further, and as some of these pressures hit further,

00:57:20.920 --> 00:57:26.680
[Guest]: China will act more responsibly, not just in terms of how it deals with conflicts, whether

00:57:26.680 --> 00:57:30.920
[Guest]: it's on its periphery, or whether it's with regard to trade, or whether it's regard to

00:57:30.920 --> 00:57:32.760
[Guest]: openness of markets.

00:57:32.760 --> 00:57:37.160
[Guest]: So that is one thing that probably makes me hopeful is that if there is some degree of

00:57:37.160 --> 00:57:45.120
[Guest]: rethink away from nationalistic rhetoric towards far more sane thought of how do we engage

00:57:45.120 --> 00:57:49.960
[Guest]: far more pragmatic approach to what's happening in the world, that can actually lead to benefits

00:57:49.960 --> 00:57:54.960
[Guest]: not just for China, but also for countries in the region, India, Japan, other Southeast

00:57:54.960 --> 00:57:56.760
[Guest]: Asian countries.

00:57:56.760 --> 00:58:04.520
[Guest]: What makes me fearful is Xi Jinping's centralization of power, his centralization of power, the

00:58:04.520 --> 00:58:10.800
[Guest]: building of a personality cult around him, which is sort of like one can reminisce, one

00:58:10.800 --> 00:58:11.960
[Guest]: does reminisce.

00:58:11.960 --> 00:58:16.280
[Guest]: And if you read Chinese academics and authors who are writing today, who have dissenting

00:58:16.280 --> 00:58:22.240
[Guest]: voices, and how some of these people are being silenced, there is a fear of China slipping

00:58:22.240 --> 00:58:28.560
[Guest]: back into the chaos of the Cultural Revolution, we are still some way away from that.

00:58:28.560 --> 00:58:32.440
[Guest]: But you're taking those first steps towards something like that.

00:58:32.440 --> 00:58:39.360
[Guest]: And that's extremely dangerous, not just for people within China, but also for the broader

00:58:39.360 --> 00:58:40.560
[Guest]: region.

00:58:40.560 --> 00:58:46.520
[Guest]: Because China today is a driver of the global economy, and to see a state like that slip

00:58:46.520 --> 00:58:50.840
[Guest]: into chaos has broader implications for people around the world.

